Skycleave: Not Without My Son~
   Dylane taps his fingers as he sits with his eyes down, waiting for you. As
you approach, he looks up with a little glimmer of hope in his sagging eyes.
He hesitates and catches himself as he begins to speak, glancing around and
then lowering his voice as you move closer.
   'I see you've gained some clout in the Black Tower,' Dylane says slowly. 'I
realize you owe me nothing, and I have spent every last penny -- every ragged
ribbon of influence. Nevertheless, I must beg your help.'
   You silently study Dylane's aging face as his eyes well up.
   'I have been to this accursed place a hundred times as it blinks in and out
across the landscape. Seen a hundred adventurers come and go. Watched the
wizards fight and fall and rise and fall and rise again. I've studied them
twice as hard since you told me what happened to my boy. There's a sorceress on
the third floor, and heaven knows they won't let me up there, but if you can
get to her and convince her, maybe there's still hope.'
   Dylane pulls a handkerchief from his pocket and blows his nose like a
trumpet. He passes you a note which simply reads, 'Annelise'.
~
   'Oh bother,' Annelise says as you interrupt her mending an old iron toaster.
She tosses it carelessly aside and pushes the hair up off her face with a sooty
hand. She brushes herself off and turns to look at you.
   'Oh dear, I didn't realize you had an appointment,' she says as she cleans
herself off using a rag. She glances over at a calendar on the desk, then back
to you, then back to the calendar. 'Well, nevermind all that. What can I do
for you, dear?'
   You weigh how to ask her for a favor for Dylane of Trense, a man you barely
know. In the end, you tell her the whole story, sparing no detail about
Dylane's teary eyes and unceasing search for his son. Well, perhaps not the
entire story. You leave out the much longer explanation about the time loop.
   'I never did like transmogrifying the students,' Annelise says with a slight
frown. 'But we certainly can't have the boy running around here. Fine, fine,
I'm sure I owe you this much. Bring him up here. Just promise me he will leave
the tower before the headmaster finds out.'
~
