and a pair of chairs scoot themselves over. She sets down two teacups and you
take a seat with her as she knits her story.
   'I was hardly a hedge witch when I got this job and I didn't know five
spells,' she says between sips of mint tea. 'The grand plan was to glean what
I could from the apprentices while earning enough money to send back to my dear
mother, with a mind to enroll as an apprentice. Can you imagine? But we didn't
know anything about the Black Tower except its reputation.
   'I had been here two years, give or take, when old Skithe severed the spell
Knezz used to unbind the tree from its original time loop, ending any ambitions
I might have had. But I was as blissfully ignorant as the rest of them. Stirred
the soup, warmed the spirits, hid behind the counter when the goblins started
shouting, got the cafe cleaned up, and then woke up to repeat it all again.'
   Mageina pauses for a moment to refill her tea with her wand. She cradles the
teacup in both hands and gently blows the steam away from the top before taking
a long drink.
   'And then a strange thing happened,' she says. 'A dashing young hero asked
for my help rescuing the tower. Me, the hedge witch scullery maid with the big
hat. Well, how could I resist? We fought Venjer and Vehl, Kara and Trixton,
Professor Barrosh, the shade... and then a strange thing happened. The shade
snatched Professor Knezz's wand and started to channel its power, but Henri
knocked it into the air with a well-timed sunshock and, in what would be the
defining moment of my entire life, I caught it.
   'And wouldn't you know, by the power of Skycleave' -- there's a low rumble
from the foundation of the tower as she says it -- 'I woke up. Not like you
wake from the dreams. Like I was waking up for the very first time. Like my
eyes had been shut my entire life. I was overwhelmed, dumbstruck, and the shade
shot out a cold tentacle, straight through my heart, and I died for the very
first time.
   'You can imagine what happened next. I woke up here, right here, at this
table, where I always do. Only, I could remember the whole thing, every moment.
I tried to talk to Professor Celiya and Instructor Huberus but they told me I
must be dreaming. I told everyone who would listen, but nobody took me
seriously. And just as I was ready to collapse from the weight of it all...
   'He walked into the cafe. My Henri. Oh, the adventures we had. We danced up
and down the tower, picnicked on the gobbrabakh, fought Mez and Knezz alike as
we studied the deep, dark magicks of the tower. Whether it was a year or a
century, I honestly could not tell you. It was forever. We were the only two
who seemed to hold onto our memories, and we cherished each other for it.'
   Mageina sets down her teacup as the light fades from her face. 'Well, it was
MY forever. Henri was trapped so much longer than I had been. I didn't realize
it at first, but by the time I woke up, he had already been through the tower
a thousand times. The burden of forever weighed on him and he began to conspire
to leave me here, alone, until that wretched lion has had her fill.
   'And so you see, here I sit, older and more powerful than any sorcerer who
has darkened these doors, unable to deal a lasting defeat to Skithe Ler-Wyn and
unable to leave the tower, at least not for long. So I make the soup, I comfort
Annelise, I listen to that vapid couple -- who, I assure you, would both be
cleaning the tower before long if not for the blessed time loop... But I take
my fate seriously. I feed them and watch over them. And when a new adventurer,
like yourself, arrives, I subtly guide them to Skycleave's secrets in hope that
some day, against all odds, a hero will arrive who can break the loop once and
for all.
   'But it's not you. I'm sorry. Your adventures in the tower have been nothing
short of legendary. But Skithe Ler-Wyn is already too powerful. I fear our last
chance to stop her has long passed, and her power still grows. I've taken steps
to keep you unbound -- I have seen days without you here; I know you can still
leave. So do it. Leave while you can. Leave us to our dark fate. Don't worry,
I'll watch over them.'
   Mageina sits for a moment longer, placing her warm hand on yours, and then
stands to return to her eternal task, leaving behind an attuned soulstone and
a fresh cup of tea for you without a further word.
~
